# Three.js Scene Graph Traversal

## Overview
Three.js organizes 3D objects in a scene graph hierarchy. Understanding this hierarchy is essential for exporting individual parts.

## Key Concepts

### Object Types
- "'`THREE.Group` — container node with transform but no geometry
- `THREE.Mesh` — leaf node with geometry + material
- `THREE.Scene` — root container (extends Group)

### Transform Chain
Each object has:
- `matrix` — local transform (position, rotation, scale relative to parent)
- `matrixWorld` — accumulated world transform (all ancestor transforms applied)
- Call `root.updateMatrixWorld(true)` before reading matrixWorld values

### Traversal Pattern
```javascript
const root = createScene();
root.updateMatrixWorld(true);

// Direct children
for (const child of group.children) {
    if (child.isMesh) { /* process mesh */ }
    if (child.isGroup) { /* recurse into group */ }
}

// Find by name
const obj = root.getObjectByName('"'my_mesh');
"'```

### Coordinate Spaces
1. **Raw geometry** — BufferGeometry positions, no transforms
2. **Local** (`mesh.matrix`) — mesh transform relative to parent
3. **Part-local** — mesh matrixWorld relative to parent group'"'s matrixWorld
4. **World** ("'`mesh.matrixWorld`) — full accumulated transform

For local == part-local when mesh is direct child of group (no intermediate transforms).

### Extracting Vertices
```javascript
const pos = geometry.attributes.position;
const v = new THREE.Vector3();
for (let i = 0; i < pos.count; i++) {
    v.set(pos.getX(i), pos.getY(i), pos.getZ(i));
    v.applyMatrix4(matrix); // apply desired transform
}
```
